node.text:
Morning meds for a kitten with kidney disease ♥️

Ferguson is thriving on this medication routine, and the best part is that he actually enjoys it! I wanted to share this sped-up look at what meds and supplements he takes every morning (and also how he takes them) in case that is helpful or interesting to you.

I use Ferguson’s favorite treats to motivate him to participate in med time. As you can see, he knows the routine and actually looks forward to these sessions! There is no one right way to work with kittens who need this much medication, but my approach is to see what works best for him, to keep everything as positive as possible, and to make adjustments as needed.

Here is what you’re seeing in the video:
-Subcutaneous fluids (LRS) with a 25g butterfly needle
-Injectable famotidine (an antacid, commonly known as Pepcid) which can be given with fluids
-Azodyl (a probiotic supporting renal health) mixed with churu
-Porous One (a uremic toxin binder) mixed with churu
-Orbax (an antibiotic)
-Clavamox (an antibiotic)
-Aluminum hydroxide (a phosphorous binder)
-He also gets injectable Cerenia (an antiemetic) which I do during his PM meds, so you don’t see that here

Please remember every case is different and you are advised to meet with a veterinary nephrology specialist to determine the right treatment for your kitten or cat! All of the medication given in this video is given under the guidance of Ferguson’s veterinary team.

🎶: The Album Leaf

node.text:
Nothing could warm my heart more than watching Ferguson play with Spud & the Buds! Here is 4 minutes of sweet playtime footage taken just a few minutes ago.

Fergie is 12 weeks old, while Spud & the Buds are about 5 weeks old…but due to his size and fragility they match really nicely for playtime. Now that the little ones are all healthy and past a nice long quarantine period, I felt comfortable letting him interact with them, and as you can see he is loving every minute!

Sadly, Ferguson is showing some physical signs of late stage kidney failure. To be completely honest, I have cried about it a lot over the past 24 hours. But then I’ll walk in the room and see him playing like this—or see him eat a big breakfast (more than half a can today!) and the only thing I can feel is happiness and hope. In spite of all he’s going through, he has such spunk and such a strong will to live a joyful life. I admire that about him so much. ♥️

UPDATE: SHE FOUND A HOME!!! ♥️ Can we all come together and help this incredible senior gal?! Skyy is 20 years old(!) but doesn’t act a day over 10. She’s loving, affectionate, and impeccably fluffy. Skyy was well-loved for her entire life, but her human recently passed away and she ended up at the humane society. She so deserves a wonderful home to live out her golden years! Will you share her video & tag friends in Southern California who might be interested in her?

Skyy is adoptable from San Diego Humane Society. Let’s boost her story & help find her an amazing home! ♥️ @sdhumanesociety

Today we took in a new foster kitten! Spud is a tiny kitten the size & development of a 5-7 day old, but if you can believe this…he’s actually 16 days old! He was born very prematurely when his mama, a feral cat, came into our local TNR clinic @feral_cat_coalition in a trap. He was the only kitten born, and his mama was not able to care for him, so he was raised for the past two weeks by the clinic manager, @aud_everything_is_taken. Audrey reached out and asked if we had any interest in taking him on, and of course, we said HECK YES!

His former foster name was Bruno, but since we have already raised a baby Bruno, we collectively decided to name him after what he looks like most — a chonky potato. As you can see, he has an incredible appetite and a rotund belly! Audrey, you did a beautiful job getting him through his most vulnerable weeks, and I’m so happy we can help carry the baton from here to adoption.

Welcome, Spud Spudley! We love you!🥔

I was so nervous about this! I wasn’t sure if Pearl would follow us on a walk or if she would run loose on our property! I needed to get her from our building to a fenced yard, and took a chance to see if she could responsibly go on a walk. She did a great job! PHEW!

Jojo is still recovering from her spay, so we are going to give the pigs another day or two apart to avoid any further #pigdrama 🐷

Thanks @dvniwhitten for helping this morning!

Fergie in the catio? Well that’s just gosh darned adorable! ☀️🌴🐈

—

I made a 30 minute video all about Ferguson, and I’ll be sharing it tomorrow morning! In the video, you’ll see clips of his life from the very moment I met him until now. You’ll hear about his history, learn about his kidney condition and the care he receives, and see a beautiful montage of his happiest moments.

If you want to watch it live with me, tune in at 9am PT on the dot. From 9-9:30 it will air as a watch party—so we can all watch it together at the same time, and there will be a special chat feature where you can ask questions & say hi! If you can’t make it at that time or are running late, no worries. It will be available to watch at your leisure anytime after 9:30. 💕

Link to watch tomorrow: bit.ly/fergvid

node.text: Ostrich and Kookaburra are SUCH a dynamic duo! 👯‍♂️ They hilariously hop around the room all day like floofy dust bunnies. Ostrich is a little flirt, and Kookaburra is a total ham who makes us laugh constantly! Both of them just adore attention and will run to the door to beg for love. These boys are definitely a bonded pair & we hope we can find them an amazing home together in the Southern California area! We’ll be adding them to the @orphankittenclub website soon, but if you’d like to get an app in for them in the meantime you are welcome to apply at orphankittenclub.org/adopt ♥️

node.text:
My last belly rubs with Jojo and Pearly Girly before they go to their new home at @centraltexaspigrescue. I can’t believe it! I will miss them so much! 😭♥️

Jojo is such a firecracker…like a big happy puppy, but so much smarter! Her enthusiasm for life is infectious & it’s been such a joy to watch her soak in new experiences since being rescued from the laboratory. Pearly Girly is such a calm, loving pig who seems so genuinely grateful to be seen and cared for. She was once the “bottom pig” at a giant hoarding case, but now she knows what it feels like to be pampered and adored. Best of all, they each know what it is to have a best friend, and they’ll get to stay that way forever. It has been such a gift to watch them each blossom and thrive.

It’s bittersweet to share these last moments with them, but I’m so grateful they have a safe and incredible place to go at @centraltexaspigrescue. Thank you, friends, for creating such an incredible place for pigs like them. Thank you @mattlieurance for braving the 20+ hour drive to get them there safely. Thank you @farmanimalrefuge and @orphankittenclub for making their rescue possible.

A lot of people don’t understand why we foster pigs. People scroll past, or say nasty things, or question why we open our home to them. But if you were here with them, your heart would immediately know why. You would fall in love. They are so social, intelligent, affectionate, and deeply deserving of care and advocacy. I wish I could personally invite each and every one of you to spend a day with them, because I think they would completely transform your understanding of and appreciation for pigs. They are truly some of the most special animals on earth—worthy of all good things. ♥️

node.text:
Morning meds for a kitten with kidney disease ♥️

Ferguson is thriving on this medication routine, and the best part is that he actually enjoys it! I wanted to share this sped-up look at what meds and supplements he takes every morning (and also how he takes them) in case that is helpful or interesting to you.

I use Ferguson’s favorite treats to motivate him to participate in med time. As you can see, he knows the routine and actually looks forward to these sessions! There is no one right way to work with kittens who need this much medication, but my approach is to see what works best for him, to keep everything as positive as possible, and to make adjustments as needed.

Here is what you’re seeing in the video:
-Subcutaneous fluids (LRS) with a 25g butterfly needle
-Injectable famotidine (an antacid, commonly known as Pepcid) which can be given with fluids
-Azodyl (a probiotic supporting renal health) mixed with churu
-Porous One (a uremic toxin binder) mixed with churu
-Orbax (an antibiotic)
-Clavamox (an antibiotic)
-Aluminum hydroxide (a phosphorous binder)
-He also gets injectable Cerenia (an antiemetic) which I do during his PM meds, so you don’t see that here

Please remember every case is different and you are advised to meet with a veterinary nephrology specialist to determine the right treatment for your kitten or cat! All of the medication given in this video is given under the guidance of Ferguson’s veterinary team.
